SIMPLE: inflammation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inflammation
<hw>In*flam*ma"tion</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*fl⟦acr⟧m*m⟦amac⟧"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>inflammatio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>inflammation</ets>. See <er>Inflame</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of inflaming, kindling, or setting on fire; also, the state
of being inflamed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>inflammation</xex> of
fat.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wilkins.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A morbid condition of any part of
the body, consisting in congestion of the blood vessels, with
obstruction of the blood current, and growth of morbid tissue. It is
manifested outwardly by redness and swelling, attended with tenderness,
heat and pain. It may be caused by exposure to any number of injurious
agents.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Violent excitement; heat; passion; animosity;
turbulence; <as>as, an <ex>inflammation</ex> of the mind, of the body
politic, or of parties</as>.</def> <rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflammative</ent>⟦br⟧
